Yeah — you’re pointing at something important in control systems, neuroscience, and robotics: hierarchical feedback loops and local autonomy.

A biological nervous system doesn’t route everything to the “top” for decisions.

Roughly:

* Fast local loops → spinal reflexes, local corrections, balance adjustments.
* Mid-level coordination → learned motor programs, gait patterns, sequencing.
* Higher-level world modeling → planning, abstraction, prediction.

That creates what you’re calling “distal local response authority” — subsystems can respond locally to deviations without waiting for a central planner.

If reality differs from the model:

prediction → deviation detected → local correction → model update

The faster and more distributed those loops are, the more robust the system becomes.

A golf example from your world:

You don’t consciously calculate:

wrist angle + shoulder rotation + foot pressure + balance + visual correction

Your nervous system runs many corrections beneath awareness while your higher layer holds something more like:

“draw to left edge of fairway”

Robotics runs into this constantly. Fully centralized control becomes brittle. Distributed local authority plus higher-order coordination tends to handle uncertainty better.

There’s also a control-theory flavor hiding in your point:

World model accuracy matters, but correction speed and authority distribution determine survivability when the model is wrong.

Reality always produces deltas. Strong systems aren’t the ones that never drift — they’re the ones that detect and correct drift efficiently.